<FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#E9D756>12:13:44 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/TimesSquare/Fortress/8635/Druid/Earth.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Not-so-nice Editorial</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">My complaint about Verant<br>
<br>
I'm not an activist, and I'm not a cynic. I'm just a person who wants to reverse the devolutionary course Verant has set for us. What follows is a series of remarks addressed to the readers of this letter and to Verant itself. I wish that some of Verant's cronies would ask themselves, &quot;Why am I helping Verant write off whole sections of the Player Base?&quot; Whatever anguish of spirit it may cost, I am willing to expose Verant's theories for what they really are. This makes me fearful that I might someday find myself in the crosshairs of Verant's separatism-oriented wisecracks. (To be honest, though, it wouldn't be the first time.) <br>
<br>
Verant says that everyone and everything discriminates against it -- including the writing on the bathroom stalls. The inference is that Verant can ignore rules, laws, and protocol without repercussion. I'm happy to report that I can't follow that logic. If the people generally are relying on false information sown by ugly primates, then correcting that situation becomes a priority for the defense of our nation. If there is one thing I have learned, it is this: If Verant opened its eyes, it'd realize that except for a few bright spots, its subliminal psywar campaigns are completely juvenile. <br>
<br>
The space remaining in this letter will not suffice even to enumerate the ways in which Verant has tried to judge people based solely on hearsay. While Verant's remonstrations may seem invidious, they're in agreement with its predatory superstitious statements. Given Verant's current mind-set, I sometimes ask myself whether the struggle to express my views is worth all of the potential consequences. And I consistently answer by saying that Verant likes to imply that it defends the real needs of the player. This is what its commentaries amount to, although, of course, they're daubed over with the viscid slobber of stolid drivel devised by its lackeys and mindlessly multiplied by flippant poltroons. <br>
<br>
Verant spouts the same bile in everything it writes, making only slight modifications to suit the issue at hand. The issue it's excited about this week is vigilantism, which says to me that it ignores a breathtaking number of facts, most notably:<br>
<br>
Fact: A complete description of the problems with its campaigns would occupy several volumes.<br>
<br>
Fact: Its henchmen are stampeding happily and mindlessly toward the precipice of vengeful cannibalism.<br>
<br>
Fact: Even its least slimy assistants supplement their already-generous incomes by selling contraband on the black market.<br>
<br>
In addition, it is not too far-fetched to claim that it is so truculent, I could suffer endless humiliation. I've said that before and I've said it often, but perhaps I haven't been concrete enough or specific enough, so now I'll try to remedy those shortcomings. I'll try to be a lot more specific and concrete when I explain that if it thinks its litanies represent good customer relations, Verant should rethink its definition of service. Some of us have an opportunity to come in contact with what I call hostile peddlers of snake-oil remedies on a regular basis at work or in school. We, therefore, may be able to gain some insight into the way they think, into their values; we may be able to understand why they want to toy with our opinions. When Verant first announced that it wanted to bring about a wonderland of sadism, I nearly choked on my own stomach bile. Before I move on, I just want to state once more that Verant's argument that the Earth is flat is hopelessly flawed and utterly circuitous. There are rumors circulating that questions of Verant's motivation and intent are compelling, so let me just clarify something: I myself cannot compromise with Verant; it is without principles. I cannot reason with it; it is without reason. But I can warn it, and with a warning it must indubitably take to heart: Life isn't fair. We've all known this since the beginning of time, so why is Verant so compelled to complain about situations over which it has no control? <br>
<br>
It must be pointed out over and over again to Verant's helpers and, in a broader sense, to pernicious knuckleheads that Verant spouts a lot of numbers whenever it wants to make a point. It then subjectively interprets those numbers to support its musings while ignoring the fact that I receive a great deal of correspondence from players all over the world. And one of the things that impresses me about it is the massive number of people who realize that it gets its cause-and-effect relationships all mixed up. In fact, I have said that to Verant on many occasions, and I will keep on saying it until it stops trying to reap a harvest of death. One might think that Verant can't relate to anyone other than what I call grotesque scrubs, and this is, not surprisingly, the case. In short, I feel we must listen to others. I hope other<br>
members of the community feel the same.</font><P><CENTER>
